{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-template-js","path":"/blog/kubernetes-api-groups-versions/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<blockquote>\n<p><strong>Core and Named Groups for the Cluster Management</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2 id=\"-introduction\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#-introduction\" aria-label=\" introduction permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>📕 Introduction</h2>\n<p>Kubernetes organizes its API into different groups based on their purpose. These groups, similar to sections in a library, hold various resources related to specific themes.</p>\n<p>The two main types of groups are the <a href=\"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/using-api/#api-groups\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">core group</a> and <a href=\"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/using-api/#api-groups\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">named groups</a>. The core group contains fundamental resources essential to the platform's operation, such as Pods, Nodes, Namespaces, and Services.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, named groups allow you to extend Kubernetes functionality by introducing custom resources and controllers related to specific areas like networking or storage. This introduction sets the stage for a deeper dive into the API groups and versions and their pivotal role in your Kubernetes journey. Let's get started!</p>\n<p><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 680px; \">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 48.23529411764706%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"API Versions\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/2aa37cc0177fbc6e3223dea04ca24741/c5bb3/api-v.png\" srcset=\"/static/2aa37cc0177fbc6e3223dea04ca24741/04472/api-v.png 170w,\n/static/2aa37cc0177fbc6e3223dea04ca24741/9f933/api-v.png 340w,\n/static/2aa37cc0177fbc6e3223dea04ca24741/c5bb3/api-v.png 680w,\n/static/2aa37cc0177fbc6e3223dea04ca24741/b12f7/api-v.png 1020w,\n/static/2aa37cc0177fbc6e3223dea04ca24741/21482/api-v.png 1350w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\">\n    </span>\n          </p>\n<h2 id=\"-why-there-are-named-groups-and-core-groups\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#-why-there-are-named-groups-and-core-groups\" aria-label=\" why there are named groups and core groups permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>📚 Why There Are Named Groups and Core Groups</h2>\n<p>Kubernetes doesn't put all its eggs in one basket. Instead, it smartly categorizes its API into different groups based on their purpose. Think of these groups like sections in a library, each holding books (or, in this case, APIs) related to a specific theme.</p>\n<p>The named groups and core groups in Kubernetes serve distinct purposes, rooted in the platform's historical and organizational principles.</p>\n<h3 id=\"core-group\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#core-group\" aria-label=\"core group permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>Core Group</h3>\n<p>The core group, also known as the legacy group, encompasses essential resources integral to Kubernetes' operation, such as Pods, Nodes, Namespaces, and Services. These resources were initially considered so fundamental to Kubernetes that they did not need to be grouped explicitly.</p>\n<p>The core group API endpoint is located at <code class=\"language-text\">/api/v1</code>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 669px; \">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 77.64705882352942%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"Core Group\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/c218ad45ed698a52b05a652a47d0b414/99272/core.png\" srcset=\"/static/c218ad45ed698a52b05a652a47d0b414/04472/core.png 170w,\n/static/c218ad45ed698a52b05a652a47d0b414/9f933/core.png 340w,\n/static/c218ad45ed698a52b05a652a47d0b414/99272/core.png 669w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 669px) 100vw, 669px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\">\n    </span>\n          </p>\n<h3 id=\"named-groups\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#named-groups\" aria-label=\"named groups permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>Named Groups</h3>\n<p>Named API groups, or namespaces, were introduced to categorize resources thematically. For instance, resources related to networking are grouped under <code class=\"language-text\">networking.k8s.io</code>. This organizational approach allows for the extension of Kubernetes functionality by introducing custom resources and controllers tailored to specific areas, such as networking or storage.</p>\n<p>The named groups API endpoint is <code class=\"language-text\">/apis/$GROUP_NAME/$VERSION</code>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 680px; \">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 64.11764705882354%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"Named Groups\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/dc2fb360737e4154b7d8cd6f081126be/c5bb3/named.png\" srcset=\"/static/dc2fb360737e4154b7d8cd6f081126be/04472/named.png 170w,\n/static/dc2fb360737e4154b7d8cd6f081126be/9f933/named.png 340w,\n/static/dc2fb360737e4154b7d8cd6f081126be/c5bb3/named.png 680w,\n/static/dc2fb360737e4154b7d8cd6f081126be/b12f7/named.png 1020w,\n/static/dc2fb360737e4154b7d8cd6f081126be/b5a09/named.png 1360w,\n/static/dc2fb360737e4154b7d8cd6f081126be/2cefc/named.png 1400w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\">\n    </span>\n          </p>\n<h3 id=\"examples-of-named-groups\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#examples-of-named-groups\" aria-label=\"examples of named groups permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>Examples of Named Groups</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>apps</strong>: Deployments, ReplicaSets, StatefulSets, DaemonSets, and DeploymentsRollback.</li>\n<li><strong>extensions</strong>: Ingresses, NetworkPolicies, and PodSecurityPolicies.</li>\n<li><strong>batch</strong>: CronJobs and Jobs.</li>\n<li><strong>storage.k8s.io</strong>: StorageClasses and VolumeAttachments.</li>\n<li><strong>policy</strong>: PodDisruptionBudgets.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 680px; \">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 52.352941176470594%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"Named Groups Examples\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/2921f390a6ce21663e4d3df9b9746c8c/c5bb3/names.png\" srcset=\"/static/2921f390a6ce21663e4d3df9b9746c8c/04472/names.png 170w,\n/static/2921f390a6ce21663e4d3df9b9746c8c/9f933/names.png 340w,\n/static/2921f390a6ce21663e4d3df9b9746c8c/c5bb3/names.png 680w,\n/static/2921f390a6ce21663e4d3df9b9746c8c/b12f7/names.png 1020w,\n/static/2921f390a6ce21663e4d3df9b9746c8c/2bef9/names.png 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\">\n    </span>\n          </p>\n<h2 id=\"️-core-group-api-endpoint\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#%EF%B8%8F-core-group-api-endpoint\" aria-label=\"️ core group api endpoint permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>🛠️ Core Group API Endpoint</h2>\n<p>The core group's API endpoint is located at <code class=\"language-text\">/api/v1</code>.</p>\n<p><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 680px; \">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 20%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"Core Group API\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/4f2081cb37f0c061444c39cf72b6992c/c5bb3/corev2.png\" srcset=\"/static/4f2081cb37f0c061444c39cf72b6992c/04472/corev2.png 170w,\n/static/4f2081cb37f0c061444c39cf72b6992c/9f933/corev2.png 340w,\n/static/4f2081cb37f0c061444c39cf72b6992c/c5bb3/corev2.png 680w,\n/static/4f2081cb37f0c061444c39cf72b6992c/b12f7/corev2.png 1020w,\n/static/4f2081cb37f0c061444c39cf72b6992c/b5a09/corev2.png 1360w,\n/static/4f2081cb37f0c061444c39cf72b6992c/2cefc/corev2.png 1400w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\">\n    </span>\n          </p>\n<h3 id=\"core-rest-path\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#core-rest-path\" aria-label=\"core rest path permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>Core REST Path</h3>\n<p><code class=\"language-text\">/api/v1</code></p>\n<h3 id=\"apiversion-field-in-the-manifest-file\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#apiversion-field-in-the-manifest-file\" aria-label=\"apiversion field in the manifest file permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>apiVersion Field in the Manifest File</h3>\n<p>The core group is not specified as part of the <code class=\"language-text\">apiVersion</code> field.</p>\n<p><span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 680px; \">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 20%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"Core API Version\" title=\"\" src=\"/static/c009fa5d1fb7851fca44142ab47706cf/c5bb3/corev3.png\" srcset=\"/static/c009fa5d1fb7851fca44142ab47706cf/04472/corev3.png 170w,\n/static/c009fa5d1fb7851fca44142ab47706cf/9f933/corev3.png 340w,\n/static/c009fa5d1fb7851fca44142ab47706cf/c5bb3/corev3.png 680w,\n/static/c009fa5d1fb7851fca44142ab47706cf/b12f7/corev3.png 1020w,\n/static/c009fa5d1fb7851fca44142ab47706cf/b5a09/corev3.png 1360w,\n/static/c009fa5d1fb7851fca44142ab47706cf/2cefc/corev3.png 1400w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\">\n    </span>\n          </p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"yaml\"><pre class=\"language-yaml\"><code class=\"language-yaml\"><span class=\"token key atrule\">apiVersion</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> v1</code></pre></div>\n<h2 id=\"-final-thoughts\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#-final-thoughts\" aria-label=\" final thoughts permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg class=\"anchor-icon\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" version=\"1.1\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7.775 3.275a.75.75 0 001.06 1.06l1.25-1.25a2 2 0 112.83 2.83l-2.5 2.5a2 2 0 01-2.83 0 .75.75 0 00-1.06 1.06 3.5 3.5 0 004.95 0l2.5-2.5a3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95-4.95l-1.25 1.25zm-4.69 9.64a2 2 0 010-2.83l2.5-2.5a2 2 0 012.83 0 .75.75 0 001.06-1.06 3.5 3.5 0 00-4.95 0l-2.5 2.5a3.5 3.5 0 004.95 4.95l1.25-1.25a.75.75 0 00-1.06-1.06l-1.25 1.25a2 2 0 01-2.83 0z\"></path></svg></a>💡 Final Thoughts</h2>\n<p>Understanding Kubernetes API groups and versions is essential for effective cluster management. The use of core and named groups, along with the ability to enable or disable API groups, provides a flexible and extensible framework for interacting with the Kubernetes API.</p>\n<p>By grasping these concepts, developers and administrators can effectively navigate and leverage the rich functionality offered by the Kubernetes API.</p>\n<p><strong>Until next time 🎉🇵🇸</strong></p>\n<p><br><br></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>💡 Thank you for Reading !! 🙌🏻😁📃, see you in the next blog.🤘  <em><strong>Until next time 🎉</strong></em></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>🚀 Thank you for sticking up till the end. If you have any questions/feedback regarding this blog feel free to connect with me:</p>\n<p><strong>♻️ LinkedIn:</strong> <a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/in/rajhi-saif/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">https://www.linkedin.com/in/rajhi-saif/</a></p>\n<p><strong>♻️ X/Twitter:</strong> <a href=\"https://x.com/rajhisaifeddine\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">https://x.com/rajhisaifeddine</a></p>\n<p><strong>The end ✌🏻</strong></p>\n<h1 align=\"center\">🔰 Keep Learning !! Keep Sharing !! 🔰</h1>\n<p><strong>📅 Stay updated</strong></p>\n<p>Subscribe to our newsletter for more insights on AWS cloud computing and containers.</p>","timeToRead":2,"rawMarkdownBody":"\n> **Core and Named Groups for the Cluster Management**\n\n## 📕 Introduction\n\nKubernetes organizes its API into different groups based on their purpose. These groups, similar to sections in a library, hold various resources related to specific themes.\n\nThe two main types of groups are the [core group](https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/using-api/#api-groups) and [named groups](https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/using-api/#api-groups). The core group contains fundamental resources essential to the platform's operation, such as Pods, Nodes, Namespaces, and Services.\n\nOn the other hand, named groups allow you to extend Kubernetes functionality by introducing custom resources and controllers related to specific areas like networking or storage. This introduction sets the stage for a deeper dive into the API groups and versions and their pivotal role in your Kubernetes journey. Let's get started!\n\n![API Versions](./api-v.png)\n\n## 📚 Why There Are Named Groups and Core Groups\n\nKubernetes doesn't put all its eggs in one basket. Instead, it smartly categorizes its API into different groups based on their purpose. Think of these groups like sections in a library, each holding books (or, in this case, APIs) related to a specific theme.\n\nThe named groups and core groups in Kubernetes serve distinct purposes, rooted in the platform's historical and organizational principles.\n\n### Core Group\n\nThe core group, also known as the legacy group, encompasses essential resources integral to Kubernetes' operation, such as Pods, Nodes, Namespaces, and Services. These resources were initially considered so fundamental to Kubernetes that they did not need to be grouped explicitly.\n\nThe core group API endpoint is located at `/api/v1`.\n\n![Core Group](./core.png)\n\n### Named Groups\n\nNamed API groups, or namespaces, were introduced to categorize resources thematically. For instance, resources related to networking are grouped under `networking.k8s.io`. This organizational approach allows for the extension of Kubernetes functionality by introducing custom resources and controllers tailored to specific areas, such as networking or storage.\n\nThe named groups API endpoint is `/apis/$GROUP_NAME/$VERSION`.\n\n![Named Groups](./named.png)\n\n### Examples of Named Groups\n\n- **apps**: Deployments, ReplicaSets, StatefulSets, DaemonSets, and DeploymentsRollback.\n- **extensions**: Ingresses, NetworkPolicies, and PodSecurityPolicies.\n- **batch**: CronJobs and Jobs.\n- **storage.k8s.io**: StorageClasses and VolumeAttachments.\n- **policy**: PodDisruptionBudgets.\n\n![Named Groups Examples](./names.png)\n\n## 🛠️ Core Group API Endpoint\n\nThe core group's API endpoint is located at `/api/v1`.\n\n![Core Group API](./corev2.png)\n\n### Core REST Path\n\n`/api/v1`\n\n### apiVersion Field in the Manifest File\n\nThe core group is not specified as part of the `apiVersion` field.\n\n![Core API Version](./corev3.png)\n\n```yaml\napiVersion: v1\n```\n\n## 💡 Final Thoughts\n\nUnderstanding Kubernetes API groups and versions is essential for effective cluster management. The use of core and named groups, along with the ability to enable or disable API groups, provides a flexible and extensible framework for interacting with the Kubernetes API.\n\nBy grasping these concepts, developers and administrators can effectively navigate and leverage the rich functionality offered by the Kubernetes API.\n\n\n**Until next time 🎉🇵🇸**\n\n<br><br>\n\n> 💡 Thank you for Reading !! 🙌🏻😁📃, see you in the next blog.🤘  _**Until next time 🎉**_\n\n🚀 Thank you for sticking up till the end. If you have any questions/feedback regarding this blog feel free to connect with me:\n\n**♻️ LinkedIn:** https://www.linkedin.com/in/rajhi-saif/\n\n**♻️ X/Twitter:** https://x.com/rajhisaifeddine\n\n**The end ✌🏻**\n\n<h1 align=\"center\">🔰 Keep Learning !! Keep Sharing !! 🔰</h1>\n\n**📅 Stay updated**\n\nSubscribe to our newsletter for more insights on AWS cloud computing and containers.\n","wordCount":{"words":498},"frontmatter":{"id":"e57575f77ff491aff31e6ce7","path":"/blog/kubernetes-api-groups-versions/","humanDate":"Oct 23, 2024","fullDate":"2024-10-23","title":"Understanding Kubernetes API Groups and Versions","keywords":["Kubernetes","API groups","API versions"],"excerpt":"Gain a comprehensive understanding of Kubernetes API groups and versions, and learn how they help manage and extend Kubernetes functionality.","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","placeholder":{"fallback":"data:image/png;base64,"},"images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/73ac542602eb0b3f86218a9fb5599be5/011c1/kubernetes-api-cover.png","srcSet":"/static/73ac542602eb0b3f86218a9fb5599be5/0dee1/kubernetes-api-cover.png 750w,\n/static/73ac542602eb0b3f86218a9fb5599be5/011c1/kubernetes-api-cover.png 1024w","sizes":"100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/73ac542602eb0b3f86218a9fb5599be5/a66aa/kubernetes-api-cover.webp 750w,\n/static/73ac542602eb0b3f86218a9fb5599be5/30a1f/kubernetes-api-cover.webp 1024w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"100vw"}]},"width":1,"height":0.5625}}},"coverCredits":"Photo by Saifeddine Rajhi"}}},"pageContext":{"prevThought":{"frontmatter":{"path":"/blog/vault-agent-secrets-injector/","title":"Securely Inject Secrets to Pods with the Vault Agent Injector","date":"2024-10-23 22:36:00"},"excerpt":"A Must-Have Tool for Securing Your Kubernetes Secrets ⭐️ Introduction In today's tech-driven world, keeping data secure is a big deal…"},"nextThought":{"frontmatter":{"path":"/blog/backtracking-docker-images/","title":"From Docker images into Dockerfile: Docker the other way around","date":"2024-10-23 22:06:00"},"excerpt":"Backtracking Docker images ⏪ 📕 Introduction Have you ever come across a Docker image that you wanted to use, but you couldn't modify it to…"}}},"staticQueryHashes":["1271460761","1321585977"],"slicesMap":{}}